<DOC><DOCNO> AP881202-0151 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-88 2024EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--China-India 1stLd-Writethru a0610 12-02 0200</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--China-India, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0610,0202</SECOND><HEAD>China Accuses India of Border Violations</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with India's response</NOTE><DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   China claimed Friday that Indian planes hadintruded into its air space, but gave no details in a statement.   India said it was not aware of any intrusions and indicated thematter would not interfere with Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's plansto visit Beijing this month, the first trip to China by an Indianprime minister since 1954.   China and India fought a brief border war in 1962 and relationshave remained tense. There have been intermittent accusations byboth sides of border violations.   The Chinese Foreign Ministry statement Friday said, ``RecentlyIndian planes have indeed intruded into China's air space. TheChinese side has made representations to the Indian side.''   The statement was issued in response to a question by the BritishBroadcasting Corp., which said a Chinese source reported borderviolations by India.   A spokesman for the Indian Foreign Ministry in New Delhi said,``We have checked with the Defense Ministry and are not aware of anyviolations. Do not read too much into the matter. Preparations forthe prime minister's visit are ... going very well.''</TEXT></DOC>